	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;">Prieston said in post <a href="http://www.eqcleric.com/forums/showthread.php?s=&postid=#post" target="_blank">#5 </a>:<br />
<b>As for being two boxed, it does not matter if there is one person running or not, each CHARACTER still needs to get his/her fair shair. The wiz was just selfishand deserved to be kicked from the group. </b></td></tr></table> <br />
<br />
Ah, the ever debated question: How do you split loot when two boxers are in the group?<br />
<br />
With me, I have someone else loot, with autosplit on, then just roll for one char on any rolled items. If the person looting doesn't want what is on the corpse, I may loot it or let it rot (or, of course, let someone else in group grab it)<br />
<br />
On the LDoN missions I have two boxed, only one char rolls for augs and items and I may or may not drop the 2nd box from group before split...I was 2 boxing for a reason, if I was doing it in LDoN, so 'they' defitely earned their share.<br />
<br />
One of my alliance guild just started a new RPS that gives the 2nd box half  points for coming on a raid to reflect their limited actions. This seems reasonably fair to me (The primary box\char still gets full points)<br />
<br />
Each char can roll, using their individual points.</font></p>
	
	<p><p><img src="/forums/images/sig_separator.gif" width="282" height="11" Alt="Hey! Watch where you point that thing!"><br>
<font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">

When you are running in circles, it is often difficult to tell whether you are ahead or behind.<br><br />
Klan ov da Grok -Lanys
</font></p></p>
